<div id="review_3409221069" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3409221069" />
    <a title="Luís" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s"><img alt="Luís" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1636480820p2/117399210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3409221069?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luís" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luís" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s">Luís</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title=" " href="/book/show/5746426-ensaio-sobre-a-cegueira">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=g-science-fiction">g-science-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=g-classics">g-classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=portugal">portugal</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=e-3">e-3</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=g-horror">g-horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3409221069" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11509805327101793629">&quot;Blindness&quot; is the most captivating novel that I have read for a long time, but also the one that I closed with the most generous relief. Its oppressive and nauseating atmosphere. Just thinking about it makes me goosebumps!<br/><br/>Imagine a pandemic that, in a few weeks, strikes blindness the population as a whole! The extraordinary and brutal dimension of the cataclysm prevents the establishment of any saving organization and generates absolute chaos.<br/>Without water, without electricity, the blind wander</span>
  <span id="freeText11509805327101793629" style="display:none">"Blindness" is the most captivating novel that I have read for a long time, but also the one that I closed with the most generous relief. Its oppressive and nauseating atmosphere. Just thinking about it makes me goosebumps!<br /><br />Imagine a pandemic that, in a few weeks, strikes blindness the population as a whole! The extraordinary and brutal dimension of the cataclysm prevents the establishment of any saving organization and generates absolute chaos.<br />Without water, without electricity, the blind wander in disparate groups in search of food which day after day is scarce in ransacked stores. The most vulnerable people die in the street amid abandoned cars and all kinds of droppings. The still-hot corpses fall prey to starving dogs, enormous rats, scavenging birds.<br />The reader accompanies a group of ten people, the very first victims of the scourge who quarantined, who in their misfortune has the unexpected luck of having a woman who can still see among them. The latter, out of prudence, pretends blindness and only her husband, an ophthalmologist, is aware of this happy anomaly of fate.<br /><br />With "Blindness", published in 1995, the future Nobel Prize winner José Saramago signs an incredibly realistic fiction in which bestiality quickly takes precedence over all humanity. Fortunately, the altruistic behaviour and intelligence of the doctor's wife somewhat attenuate the surrounding darkness!<br />This fiction's strangeness must accentuate by the Portuguese writer's particular syntax in which the comma is queen.<br /><br />Glued continuously to the basques of the protagonists in their groping movements, the reader stunned by the apocalyptic degree of the intrigue will do until the end. Round-eyed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11509805327101793629" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


